title: Veganism ‘on the way out’ despite grocers unveiling plant-based options
description: Sky News contributor Joe Hildebrand says veganism is “on the way out” despite grocers unveiling plant-based options.   “Vegan food is on the way out,” Mr Hildebrand said.  “The collapse of the vegan boom … 2019 was the year of the vegan.”

title: ‘Life got harder’: RBA delivers a blow to homeowners
description: On tonight’s episode of Paul Murray Live, Sky News host Paul Murray discusses mortgages, the RBA, cost of living and more.

title: Activist group Teachers for Palestine to flout Chris Minns’ restrictions
description: Sky News host Freya Leach says activist group Teachers for Palestine will flout Chris Minns’ new restrictions.   “The Teachers for Palestine group in New South Wales has said they will flout Chris Minns’ new restrictions on what they can and can’t say in the classroom,” Ms Leach said.  “They will continue to encourage people to use slogans like ‘globalise the intifada’.”

title: ‘Very deep trouble’: Starmer is tying the UK back to the European Union
description: Reform UK Leader Nigel Farage criticises UK Prime Minister Kier Starmer for tying the UK to the European Union.   “We have an unimaginative Prime Minister in very, very deep trouble,” Mr Farage told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “Piece by piece, he’s tying us back ever more closely to the European Union.   “We never properly left, legally we left, constitutionally we left, but we still stayed part of the court of human rights.”

title: ‘Mainstream media cannot be trusted’ as they slam documentary ‘Melania’
description: Sky News host Andrew Bolt discusses the mainstream media’s bias against First Lady Melania’s documentary.  “A real pile on,” Mr Bolt said.  “Let’s all unite by hating Melania.”

title: ‘Very important’: Nigel Farage advises Pauline Hanson to be careful of ‘defectors’
description: Reform UK Leader Nigel Farage gives advice to One Nation Leader Pauline Hanson.  “If people are coming to you because they want to save their own political skins, reject them,” Mr Farage told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “Getting it right is very, very important.“

title: ‘Very well received’: Melania beats box office predictions
description: Former White House Press secretary Sean Spicer says Melania’s box office predictions are rising in spite of the left’s outburst.  “I’m not one of those people that likes to cheer at a movie theatre,” Mr Spicer said.  “It was very, very well received.”

title: Ben Bankas’ six sold out shows get cancelled after joking about Renee Good
description: Comedian Alex Stein talks about how Ben Bankas got his six sold-out shows in Minnesota cancelled because he joked about Renee Good.   “That cancellation actually got him a bunch of good publicity,” Mr Stein told Sky News host Rita Panahi.  “The more they try to cancel … the bigger they get.”

title: ‘Complete echo chamber’: Universities are ‘teaching how great communism is’
description: Sussex University Reform Society President Dylan Caddick criticises the Sussex University campus for its hostility towards free speech.  “People don’t speak up, you’re worried about everything you say,” Mr Caddick told Sky News host Peta Credlin.   “It’s just a complete echo chamber I’ve found.  “They’ll teach about how great communism is.”

title: ‘Strong chance’ Angus Taylor may challenge Sussan Ley’s Liberal leadership
description: Sky News Political Editor Andrew Clennell says there is a “strong chance” Shadow Defence Minister Angus Taylor may challenge Opposition Leader Sussan Ley for the Liberal leadership if tensions with the National Party persist.  “I think there is a strong chance, but it’s ultimately going to be determined by numbers,” Mr Clennell told Sky News host Peta Credlin.  “He has to peel off a couple of people, and I’m not sure he has done that yet.  “He’s hoping, I think, that a week of this divided Opposition in parliament will get some of these wavering colleagues to change their minds and come to him.”

title: ‘Now I’m a big Nicki fan’: Minaj gains more fame amid Trump controversy
description: Comedian Alex Stein respects Nicki Minaj for “calling it like she sees it and just being honest” amid her fandom for US President Donald Trump.  “The more they attack somebody, the bigger and stronger that person gets,” Mr Stein told Sky News host Rita Panahi.  “The more they try to cancel someone, I think it has a reverse effect where actually they gain a lot more fame.  I think it has a reverse effect where actually they gain a lot more fame.”

title: ‘Only just the beginning’: Farage warns of names in the Epstein files
description: Reform UK Leader Nigel Farage warns that it is only just the beginning for those names in the Epstein files.   “For the royal family, what began as an embarrassment has turned into a disaster,” Mr Farage told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “I have a feeling that this scandal is only just beginning.”

title: Druze group calls councillor ‘antisemitic’ after she questioned giving them 75k
description: Sky News host Caleb Bond supports Kingston Councillor Caroline White after she questioned why the Druze group received 75 thousand in funding for an event not in their area.   “I’m sorry, but you got 75 grand, which was pretty generous,” Mr Bond said.   “A council says maybe we should consider spending money in our own council area.  “Now they’re going to go, I’ll persecute you under hate speech laws, and by the way, you’re antisemitic.”

title: ‘So weak’: Starmer approves Chinese ‘fortress’ experts warn will be used for espionage activity
description: Sky News host Freya Leach criticised UK Prime Minister Kier Starmer for allowing China to build a new Embassy.   “They do boss western countries around,” Ms Leach said.   “We’ve become so weak.  “We just let ourselves get blackmailed and bullied by China, and we just roll over.   “This mega Embassy is 55 thousand square meters, 200 underground rooms, including underground communications cables. This thing is basically a fortress in the heart of London.  “Many security experts are worried will be used as a hub for massive espionage activities.”

title: ‘Not of sound mind’: Celebrities need to stop naming their children ridiculous names
description: Sky News host Caleb Bond criticises parents for naming their children ridiculous names.   “We really need to give out licences to have children,” Mr Bond said.  “You're clearly not of sound mind. You do not deserve to have a child in your custody. There is something wrong with you.”
